POST-INSTALL:

                * Create a directory named ~/.mlterm in your home-directory 
                with three files: "main", "font", "color" and "key".

                - File main:

		ENCODING = utf8
		fontsize = 20
		receive_string_via_ucs = true
		use_anti_alias = false
		use_transbg = false
		wall_picture = 
		mod_meta_mode = esc
		scrollbar_mode = none
		use_bidi = true
		bg_color = prev_bg
		fg_color = prev_fg
		brightness = 100
		contrast = 100
		gamma = 100
		fade_ratio = 90

		- File font:

		ISO10646_UCS2_1 = 20,-arabeyes-fixed-medium-r-normal--20-200-75-75-c-100-ISO10646-1;
		#ISO8859_1 = --sony-fixed-medium-r-normal--16-150-75-75-c-80-iso8859-1;
		#BIG5 = -eten-fixed-medium-r-normal--16-150-75-75-c-160-big5.eten-0;
		#ISO10646_UCS4_1 = -gnu-unifont-medium-r-normal--16-160-75-75-c-80-iso10646-1;
		#ISO10646_UCS4_1_BIWIDTH = -gnu-unifont-medium-r-normal--16-160-75-75-c-80-iso10646-1;

		- File color:

		prev_fg    = #DDDDDD
		prev_bg    = #000000
		red        = #CC3333
		green      = #33CC33
		yellow     = #CCCC33
		blue       = #3333CC
		magenta    = #CC33CC
		cyan       = #33CCCC
		white      = #CCCCCC
		hl_red     = #FF6666
		hl_green   = #66FF66
		hl_yellow  = #FFFF66
		hl_blue    = #6666FF
		hl_magenta = #FF66FF
		hl_cyan    = #66FFFF
		hl_white   = #FFFFFF
		

                -File key:

                EXT_KBD=Control+backslash


NOTES:

                * Now once you start mlterm, you should be able to read Arabic
                 under any text-based application that supports UTF-8. Also, 
                 note that less may not work unless you set the LESSCHARSET 
                 environment to 'UTF-8'.
                 In order to input in Arabic all you have to do is
                 Ctrl-\ (or whatever else you would like to define in
                 your key file. 
